From its manufacturing roots, Lean Six-sigma today has  evolved into a set of customer-centric, throughput and quality  related principles as to how teams should organize  themselves to provide the best value to customers without  wasting any effort that the final customer is not ready to pay  for. Lean Six-sigma leaders take the view that the price their  products or services command in the market is based only on  the value that the product or service provides to the customer.

- ## Limits
#Limits  #ValueNeutrality #General #Feature #Value #ValueBased #Software #Engineering #Software #Engineering 
Traditional requirements processes are primarily “product  focused” rather than “customer focused”. In other words,  traditional requirements specification processes focus on  identifying product features and specifying them to the extent  that they can be implemented in the system and later tested  [25, 19]. These activities are necessary in order to implement  any system. However, the elicitation of information from the  customer is focused on the product. As a result, the handling  of customer value drivers is rudimentary and incidental if  done at all. There are numerous examples in the literature of  system development projects where the wrong system was  Customer  Value  Assessment  Value  Implementation  Quantitative  Value  Assessment developed because the requirements were incorrect [26,27].  Numerous authors point out that requirements defects are the  most common and the most costly to correct [19, 3].  Recent efforts have improved requirements gathering and  specification processes by creating Use Cases which identify  task scenarios that a customer wants to achieve though using  the proposed system [15, 23]. This is a necessary step,  however, again the focus is on the system features that need  to be created to facilitate the customer accomplishing the task  as opposed to customer perceptions and identifying what  factors drive consumer choice.

- ## 1.
#1. #Customer #Value #Assessment #Phases #Feature #Value #ValueBased #Software #Engineering #Software #Engineering 
Customer Value Assessment  (CVA) provides a sophisticated and systematic assessment of  customer attitudes, motivations and preferences around the  company and product under study. This assessment is  strategic in that it provides deep insight into customer  decision making, motivations and choice. This information is  essential to:  • Understanding what feature sets are most important to  customers  • What aspects of those feature sets drive the customer’s  purchasing decision  • How much customers are willing to pay for these features.  The information acquired through the CVA is vital for  successful product introduction and winning market share.
